  (1991a) divide distinctions between the source language and the target language into two categories: translation divergences, in which the same infor- mation is conveyed in the source and target exts, but the structures of the sentences are different (as in previous work by Dorr [1990a, 1990b]); and translation mismatches, in which the information that is conveyed is different in the source and target lan- guages (as described by Kameyama et al.
